org.gearvrf

Interface GVRShaderManagers<MAP,ID>

  • Type Parameters:
    MAP - The name mapping object, GVRMaterialMap or GVRPostEffectMap.
    ID - The opaque types GVRCustomMaterialShaderId and GVRCustomPostEffectShaderId that keep the 'object' and 'scene' shader's namespaces separate, and eliminate the possibility that you could use an object shader id where you mean to use a scene shader id, and vice versa. You can pass an ID instance to getShaderMap(ID); additionally
    • You can pass an object shader ID to GVRMaterial.GVRMaterial(GVRContext, GVRMaterialShaderId) or GVRMaterial.setShaderType(GVRMaterialShaderId).
    • You can pass an scene shader ID to GVRPostEffect.GVRPostEffect(GVRContext, GVRPostEffectShaderId) or GVRPostEffect.setShaderType(GVRPostEffectShaderId).
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    GVRBaseShaderManager, GVRMaterialShaderManager, GVRPostEffectShaderManager

    public interface GVRShaderManagers<MAP,ID>
    The API shared by GVRMaterialShaderManager and GVRPostEffectShaderManager.

    GVRMaterialShaderManager implements GVRShaderManagers GVRMaterialMap implements GVRShaderMaps GVRMaterial implements GVRShaders
    GVRPostEffectShaderManager implements GVRShaderManagers GVRPostEffectMap implements GVRShaderMaps GVRPostEffect implements GVRShaders

      • addShader

        ID addShader(java.lang.String pathPrefix,
             java.lang.String vertexShader_asset,
             java.lang.String fragmentShader_asset)
        Builds a shader program from the supplied vertex and fragment shader code. The main point of this API is 'discovery,' where you scan the asset directory (or, more typically, some particular subdirectory) looking for shader pairs that you didn't know about at compile time. Secondarily, this can be useful if you have a lot of shader pairs, and would prefer to create a folder per pair and use names like "thisShader/vertex.vsh" and "thisShader/fragment.fsh" rather than "thisShader_vertex.vsh" and "thisShader_fragment.fsh". If neither of this points applies to you, you should use res/raw and the addShader(int, int) overload, as that presents no dangers of file not found exceptions.
        Parameters:
        pathPrefix - Optional (may be null) prefix for shader filenames. If present, will be prepended to vertexShader and fragmentShader, thus allowing you to build a tree of shaders in your assets directory, where each node contains vertex and fragment shaders with the same filename. If null, vertexShader and fragmentShader are the path names of files in the assets directory.

        To be clear: the path names can contain '/' characters, whether or not pathPrefix is null. 

         
 pathPrefix = "foo"; fragmentShader = "bar/fragment.fsh"
 // Asset-relative name is "foo/bar/fragment.fsh" 
 
 pathPrefix = null; fragmentShader = "bar/fragment.fsh"
 // Asset-relative name is "bar/fragment.fsh"
        vertexShader_asset - Filename of a vertex shader, relative to the assets directory
        fragmentShader_asset - Filename of a fragment shader, relative to the assets directory
        Returns:
        An opaque type that you can pass to getShaderMap(ID), or to the GVRMaterial and GVRPostEffect constructors and setShader methods ... or null on any exception, which typically would mean that one or both of the files does not exist or is not readable.

      • addShader

        ID addShader(int vertexShader_resRaw,
             int fragmentShader_resRaw)
        Builds a shader program from the supplied vertex and fragment shader code. If you are not doing 'discovery' (scanning the asset directory for shader pairs that you don't know about at compile time) this API is preferable to addShader(String, String, String), as Android tools can guarantee that the res/raw file exists.
        Parameters:
        vertexShader_resRaw - R.raw id, for a file containing a vertex shader
        fragmentShader_resRaw - R.raw id, for a file containing a fragment shader
        Returns:
        An opaque type that you can pass to getShaderMap(ID), or to the GVRMaterial and GVRPostEffect constructors and setShader methods.

      • addShader

        ID addShader(java.io.InputStream vertexShader_stream,
             java.io.InputStream fragmentShader_stream)
        Builds a shader program from the supplied vertex and fragment shader code. This overload is used inside of addShader(int, int) and addShader(String, String). It may not be incredibly useful to application code, but has been exposed because there's no real reason to keep it hidden.
        Parameters:
        vertexShader_stream - GLSL source code for a vertex shader. Stream will be closed when method returns.
        fragmentShader_stream - GLSL source code for a fragment shader. Stream will be closed when method returns.
        Returns:
        An opaque type that you can pass to getShaderMap(ID), or to the GVRMaterial and GVRPostEffect constructors and setShader methods.
